Also, resources are very limited.

00:01:35.099 --> 00:01:36.959
We are a developing nation.

00:01:36.959 --> 00:01:38.559
We are, again, developing,

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:41.660
but still, resources are quite scarce.

00:01:41.660 --> 00:01:43.080
Also, Colombia has a lot of people,

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:44.919
has over 50 million people.

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:47.160
That's a lot of people, a lot of patients,

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:50.959
and those patients are very well being taken care of.

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:53.160
Like, 99% of people are covered

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:54.800
by the Colombian healthcare system,

00:01:55.519 --> 00:01:57.680
which a lot of healthcare systems can't say the same.

00:01:57.680 --> 00:01:59.599
So it's 99% of 50 million people.

00:01:59.599 --> 00:02:01.639
That's a lot of people, and most of those people,

00:02:01.639 --> 00:02:02.879
not most of those people,

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:05.199
about half live in rural areas.

00:02:05.199 --> 00:02:07.440
So, yeah, it's quite difficult.

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:09.800
And I started my career working in data science

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:11.320
and healthcare in Colombia,

00:02:11.320 --> 00:02:12.919
and I did a lot of things,

00:02:12.919 --> 00:02:15.039
mainly data enrichment pipelines.

00:02:15.039 --> 00:02:17.919
Also, I worked in risk and fraud detection,

00:02:17.919 --> 00:02:19.759
so an invoice comes in.

00:02:19.759 --> 00:02:20.720
Is it fraudulent?

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:22.860
Is it something that we should pay for?

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:24.339
Is it something that not?

00:02:24.339 --> 00:02:26.100
Again, the resources are quite scarce,

00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:29.139
so if we can avoid paying for invoices,

00:02:29.139 --> 00:02:31.460
then perhaps we're saving a lot of people's lives.

00:02:31.460 --> 00:02:34.139
Also, these have to be done in real time, right?

00:02:34.139 --> 00:02:36.940
If you get an invoice, you gotta pay it very soon, right?

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:40.100
You don't have like a year to get some data,

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:41.460
analyze it, and then in a year,

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:42.419
decide if you pay it or not.

00:02:42.419 --> 00:02:44.899
This had to be done almost in real time.

00:02:44.899 --> 00:02:47.380
Also, this had to be done on-site.

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:50.440
So this was about 2018, 2019.

00:02:51.539 --> 00:02:53.699
Back in those days, healthcare and cloud

00:02:54.059 --> 00:02:54.899
didn't mix very well.

00:02:54.899 --> 00:02:57.139
I think they still don't mix very well.

00:02:57.139 --> 00:02:58.339
This was before the pandemic,

00:02:58.339 --> 00:03:01.020
so if it doesn't mix very well now,

00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:02.360
it didn't back then.

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:04.460
So this was the server that I had to run

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:07.059
all of my data pipelines and everything on.

00:03:07.059 --> 00:03:08.580
That's the server.

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:11.220
If I reach the resource limit of that server,

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:13.100
too bad, it has to run in that.

00:03:13.100 --> 00:03:15.899
And I wrote also, well, a very limited budget,

00:03:15.899 --> 00:03:18.580
again, especially in terms of hardware.

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:20.259
And all of this was written

00:03:20.259 --> 00:03:22.860
in our favorite programming language, R.

00:03:22.860 --> 00:03:25.139
And let me go back to here.

00:03:25.139 --> 00:03:26.580
It was all written in R,

00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:28.699
which, very lovely programming language.

00:03:28.699 --> 00:03:30.580
We all here love R.

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:34.460
But the truth is that this did not scale, right?

00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:36.500
So I was trying to run way too much

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:37.940
on too little hardware.

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:39.020
The hardware wasn't even that bad,

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:40.300
but it was just a lot of things

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:41.940
trying to run really quickly,

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:43.419
and things did not scale.

00:03:43.419 --> 00:03:45.380
So what was the answer?

00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:46.860
How did we fix this problem?

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:48.179
How did we make it scale?

00:03:48.179 --> 00:03:50.619
Of course, the answer is Rust.

00:03:50.619 --> 00:03:52.500
That's why I'm giving this presentation.

00:03:53.179 --> 00:03:55.020
So that's why Rust is important to me

00:03:55.020 --> 00:03:57.059
and why I love it so much.

00:03:57.059 --> 00:03:58.979
So now we can go back to the original question.

00:03:58.979 --> 00:04:00.580
What is Rust?

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:03.300
And Rust is, I could start saying

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:05.740
it's a programming language based on whatever.

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:07.059
That doesn't really matter.

00:04:07.059 --> 00:04:09.100
Rust is a programming language

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:10.619
empowering everyone to build

00:04:10.619 --> 00:04:12.660
reliable and efficient software.

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:13.740
That is its main goal,

00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:15.619
and that's its definition.

00:04:15.619 --> 00:04:17.420
This is according to the website.

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:20.260
So how does Rust do this?

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:22.299
Rust has three main promises.

00:04:23.059 --> 00:04:23.899
The first one is performance.

00:04:23.899 --> 00:04:25.579
So Rust has to be fast.

00:04:25.579 --> 00:04:27.380
It has to run very well.

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:28.940
It also has reliability.

00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:31.619
So people need to be able to rely on it.

00:04:31.619 --> 00:04:32.540
Yeah, it can be fast,

00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:34.820
but it's inconsistent.

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:37.019
It deals to weird behavior.

00:04:37.019 --> 00:04:38.940
No, it needs to be very reliable.

00:04:38.940 --> 00:04:40.299
And it also needs to be productive.

00:04:40.299 --> 00:04:42.500
So yeah, sure, you can write Rust,

00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:44.059
but it takes like 10 months

00:04:44.059 --> 00:04:45.059
to write anything in Rust,

00:04:45.059 --> 00:04:45.899
and it's not worth it.

00:04:45.899 --> 00:04:47.299
It also needs to be productive.

00:04:47.299 --> 00:04:48.820
So these are the three main goals

00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:50.899
and promises of the Rust programming language.

00:04:50.899 --> 00:04:53.779
And I want to focus on specifically one of them,

00:04:53.779 --> 00:04:55.779
and more specifically a single part

00:04:55.779 --> 00:04:59.220
of the message on the performance one,

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:00.739
which is that it must easily integrate

00:05:00.739 --> 00:05:02.140
with other languages.

00:05:02.140 --> 00:05:04.940
So the point of Rust is not to replace everything,

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:07.179
although for some people it might seem like that,

00:05:07.179 --> 00:05:08.459
but it's also to easily integrate

00:05:08.459 --> 00:05:09.339
with other languages.

00:05:09.339 --> 00:05:10.459
And that's why I'm here.

00:05:10.459 --> 00:05:12.820
We're talking about R and Rust together.

00:05:12.820 --> 00:05:16.100
So how can the R ecosystem benefit from Rust?

00:05:16.100 --> 00:05:17.820
There are many ways it can.

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:18.899
One of them is packages,

00:05:18.899 --> 00:05:19.899
another one is tools,

00:05:19.899 --> 00:05:21.820
and another one is culture.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:24.339
We're gonna kind of go through them in order,

00:05:24.339 --> 00:05:26.299
and I'm gonna start with packages.

00:05:26.299 --> 00:05:28.380
So to answer this very hard question

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:31.059
of how can the R ecosystem benefit from Rust,

00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:33.859
I'm gonna take a little bit of a step back

00:05:33.859 --> 00:05:37.260
and look at one of our sibling data communities,

00:05:37.260 --> 00:05:39.100
which is the Python ecosystem.

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:43.299
So how is the Python ecosystem benefiting from Rust today?

00:05:43.299 --> 00:05:45.000
This is a little plot I made.

00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:48.940
I went and downloaded all of the packages

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:50.579
published to PyPy.

00:05:50.579 --> 00:05:52.260
For you guys that don't know what PyPy is,

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:55.660
PyPy is like the CRAN of Python,

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:57.980
so it's where people publish Python packages.

00:05:57.980 --> 00:05:59.299
It's different from CRAN,

00:05:59.299 --> 00:06:01.619
but it's sort of that gist of it,

00:06:01.619 --> 00:06:04.660
kind of like the R multipliers that we just saw.

00:06:04.660 --> 00:06:07.980
And we can see packages that use C++,

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:10.820
that use Cython, which is like a domain-specific

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:15.540
Python C language, and also Rust.

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:18.640
And you can see Rust very quickly

00:06:19.339 --> 00:06:20.839
becoming one of the dominant languages

00:06:20.839 --> 00:06:22.839
that people extend Python with.

00:06:22.839 --> 00:06:26.160
Nowadays, in 2025, from what's come of the year,

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:27.519
one out of every three packages

00:06:27.519 --> 00:06:30.119
that need native code in Python use Rust,

00:06:30.119 --> 00:06:33.079
which is huge for a language that's very new,

00:06:33.079 --> 00:06:36.640
and the exponential curve is very clearly seen right there.

00:06:38.079 --> 00:06:39.559
So what are these packages?

00:06:39.559 --> 00:06:41.320
There are so many packages being published

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:43.720
in the Python ecosystem using Rust.

00:06:43.720 --> 00:06:45.239
What are those packages about?

00:06:45.239 --> 00:06:46.820
Well, a lot of them about AI.

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:51.500
So anyone that uses AI or has used WhisperX,

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:53.140
you've probably used a Rust package already.

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:55.299
So OpenAI, StickToken, the Tokenizer,

00:06:55.299 --> 00:06:57.660
or HuggingFaces, VectorDatabases,

00:06:57.660 --> 00:06:59.859
if you are doing RAG and experimenting with RAG,

00:06:59.859 --> 00:07:02.459
you're probably using Rust already in the Python ecosystem.

00:07:02.459 --> 00:07:04.579
As you can see, there's a very dominant color,

00:07:04.579 --> 00:07:07.859
which is like this little pinkish-reddish color,

00:07:07.859 --> 00:07:09.959
which is Rust on GitHub.

00:07:09.959 --> 00:07:12.239
Also, data lakes and data processing

00:07:12.239 --> 00:07:14.059
have a lot of Rust in them.

00:07:14.059 --> 00:07:15.980
So if you've used folders,

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:17.779
a lot of the demos we've seen here at Posit.com

00:07:17.779 --> 00:07:19.000
have used folders.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:20.540
Folders is a data frame library

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:24.440
that has a Python interface, but has a Rust core.

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:26.279
Also, things with Delta tables,

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:29.579
so if you've ever had to interact with a Delta lake,

00:07:29.579 --> 00:07:32.140
you've probably also used Rust from the Python ecosystem,

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:33.779
and there are a bunch of other packages

00:07:33.779 --> 00:07:37.359
in data processing and data engineering on the Python side

00:07:37.359 --> 00:07:40.100
that, underneath the hood, use Rust

00:07:40.100 --> 00:07:44.100
to make themselves fast, reliable, and productive.

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.440
So by now, I think it's very clear

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:48.420
that the Python ecosystem is leveraging Rust

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:50.399
to make itself way better.

00:07:50.399 --> 00:07:51.459
So how about R?

00:07:51.459 --> 00:07:55.559
How can R tap into that success and become better as well?

00:07:56.739 --> 00:07:58.459
Well, one of the answers, because there are many,

00:07:58.459 --> 00:08:01.380
is Extender, or R Extender on CRAN,

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:03.739
if you want to install it on your machine.

00:08:03.739 --> 00:08:06.179
Extender is a way of taking Rust code

00:08:06.179 --> 00:08:08.540
and running it inside your R sessions.

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:10.100
So it's kind of like RCPP,

00:08:10.100 --> 00:08:12.500
so it's a way of extending R with Rust,

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:13.540
and it's very cool.

00:08:13.940 --> 00:08:16.420
So here's a little R function that I wrote.

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:18.019
I took some elements from a string,

00:08:18.019 --> 00:08:19.739
I split them up by a comma,

00:08:19.739 --> 00:08:22.859
converted them to numbers, and kind of summed them up.

00:08:22.859 --> 00:08:25.339
I thought of this function because it was complex enough

00:08:25.339 --> 00:08:28.859
that it would be beneficial to maybe add some performance

00:08:28.859 --> 00:08:30.239
with it using native code,

00:08:30.239 --> 00:08:35.239
but also not complex enough to fill out a whole screen.

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:36.780
So I can take this code

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:39.359
and magically transform it into Rust code,

00:08:39.359 --> 00:08:40.539
which is different.

00:08:40.539 --> 00:08:42.500
Rust code is not R code.

00:08:42.500 --> 00:08:45.099
But also, there's map, there's flatten.

00:08:45.099 --> 00:08:47.219
The functions don't look that different.

00:08:47.219 --> 00:08:49.140
There are some similarities in there.

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:51.539
And there's this little Extender macro

00:08:51.539 --> 00:08:53.820
or Extender decorator on the top,

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:56.200
and that means, hey, Extender,

00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:58.739
make this function available from R.

00:08:58.739 --> 00:09:01.739
And by adding this, we can magically use it from R.

00:09:01.739 --> 00:09:03.179
So I wrote this little benchmark

00:09:03.179 --> 00:09:06.640
where I just generated a bunch of random strings

00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:07.859
to sum them up.

00:09:07.859 --> 00:09:10.179
I created a benchmark and compared the results,

00:09:10.179 --> 00:09:13.539
and you can kind of see the Rust line over there.

00:09:13.539 --> 00:09:14.380
It's very small.

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:16.200
It's very fast code.

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:17.039
It's native code.

00:09:17.039 --> 00:09:18.979
This is running on machine code.

00:09:18.979 --> 00:09:21.700
And it was as easy as that

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:23.500
to integrate both of the languages.

00:09:24.619 --> 00:09:26.859
This is an 18x improvement in performance,

00:09:26.859 --> 00:09:29.659
and for more complex logic, that would probably be better.

00:09:29.659 --> 00:09:32.299
Even if we added parallelization and stuff,

00:09:32.299 --> 00:09:34.619
we could go into the 100x's.

00:09:34.619 --> 00:09:36.039
We've actually had to do this

00:09:36.039 --> 00:09:38.059
in projects with different clients.

00:09:38.059 --> 00:09:40.780
So for a Fortune 500 client that we have,

00:09:40.780 --> 00:09:42.659
they needed to do very fast queries

00:09:42.659 --> 00:09:44.440
on a directed acyclic graph.

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:45.280
For you guys that don't know

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:46.859
what a directed acyclic graph is,

00:09:46.859 --> 00:09:50.460
it's finding relationships between nodes.

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:52.380
And this is a problem that is,

00:09:52.380 --> 00:09:54.859
I mean, there are a lot of good libraries that solve this.

00:09:54.859 --> 00:09:56.260
iGraph is one of them.

00:09:56.260 --> 00:09:58.739
But we need it to be very, very performant,

00:09:58.739 --> 00:10:00.020
and we need to specialize

00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:02.820
on these sort of directed acyclic graphs.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:05.380
So we built a package called ORFweaver.

00:10:05.380 --> 00:10:06.340
It's in CRAN.

00:10:06.340 --> 00:10:07.500
It's mostly written in R.

00:10:07.940 --> 00:10:09.340
And there is some rust in there.

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:12.099
And that rust is to specifically optimize

00:10:12.099 --> 00:10:14.780
those directed acyclic graph queries.

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:16.739
And it's a very fast package.

00:10:16.739 --> 00:10:18.820
There's a bunch of benchmarks

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:20.700
compared to iGraph over there.

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:22.719
It doesn't do as much as iGraph,

00:10:22.719 --> 00:10:24.619
but what it does, it does really fast.

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:27.780
So I think it's very clear that we can benefit

00:10:27.780 --> 00:10:30.739
in the Oracle system by making better packages,

00:10:30.739 --> 00:10:33.580
faster packages, and leveraging rust to make them.

00:10:33.580 --> 00:10:35.099
But how about tools?

00:10:35.099 --> 00:10:36.659
Tools is one of these things that,

00:10:36.659 --> 00:10:37.859
to me, are very important.

00:10:37.859 --> 00:10:39.739
There's been a lot of talk about tools.

00:10:39.739 --> 00:10:41.159
There was even a keynote,

00:10:41.159 --> 00:10:43.619
a lot about tools and Positron being a tool.

00:10:43.619 --> 00:10:45.840
So what about tools?

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:48.340
I'm gonna talk about one tool that was just mentioned.

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:51.500
So the R Installation Manager, or RIG.

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:52.780
RIG is an amazing tool.

00:10:52.780 --> 00:10:55.580
If you've ever had to install multiple versions of R,

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:57.140
you know it can be a headache.

00:10:57.140 --> 00:10:59.880
Like, it used to be a nightmare.

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:01.419
Nowadays, it's a non-problem.

00:11:01.419 --> 00:11:04.200
Just RIG add, and you'll get a new version.

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:05.840
And this is written in rust.

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:09.580
So this is me typing up my password wrong like three times.

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:14.580
Things, just things that happen, right?

00:11:14.580 --> 00:11:18.159
But it was harder to type my password

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:21.000
than it was to install a new R version.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:26.000
So yeah, that just goes to how good RIG of a tool is.

00:11:27.239 --> 00:11:29.320
There's also another one that, actually,

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:31.119
Davis and Lionel gave a talk on yesterday

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:32.320
that's called Air.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:35.719
Air is a very fast, very good R formatter,

00:11:35.719 --> 00:11:37.299
also written in rust.

00:11:37.299 --> 00:11:40.119
So these tools that need performance

00:11:40.119 --> 00:11:43.280
to make themselves good to the users,

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:44.880
rust is a very good answer for them.

00:11:44.880 --> 00:11:47.219
Rust is empowering them to build these sort of tools.

00:11:47.219 --> 00:11:49.840
This is me just typing out random code

00:11:49.840 --> 00:11:51.239
and I'll save immediately.

00:11:51.239 --> 00:11:54.000
And you can see, boom, gets formatted immediately.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:55.599
This was shown in their talk yesterday,

00:11:55.599 --> 00:11:58.840
but again, it's super cool and it really does help.

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:00.820
So now formatting is not something

00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:04.260
that my team is spending their pull request

00:12:04.260 --> 00:12:05.659
review time on.

00:12:05.659 --> 00:12:07.900
Formatting is just something that's done by default.

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:10.940
Again, it's a no-brainer, it's a non-problem.

00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:12.859
So that's what tooling is.

00:12:12.859 --> 00:12:14.479
That's what rust is enabling with tooling.

00:12:14.479 --> 00:12:16.580
So now let's move on to culture.

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:18.580
Culture is a little bit more abstract.

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:20.140
So tools are quite concrete, like,

00:12:20.140 --> 00:12:22.299
oh, I can install RIG, I can install Air,

00:12:22.299 --> 00:12:24.659
I can install Arc or whatever.

00:12:24.659 --> 00:12:25.859
For packages, it's the same.

00:12:25.859 --> 00:12:27.780
I can write better, faster packages.

00:12:27.780 --> 00:12:29.500
What does culture mean?

00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:32.419
I'm gonna show a little bit of a quote from Linus Torvalds.

00:12:32.419 --> 00:12:34.739
For you guys that don't know who Linus Torvalds is,

00:12:34.739 --> 00:12:37.099
how many of you guys know who Linus Torvalds is?

00:12:37.099 --> 00:12:39.419
Okay, everyone knows who Linus Torvalds is.

00:12:39.419 --> 00:12:41.700
But Linus Torvalds is the maintainer of the Linux kernel.

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:44.679
So anyone that's ever deployed to Linux,

00:12:44.679 --> 00:12:47.299
you have to thank this guy for building that.

00:12:47.299 --> 00:12:48.900
He doesn't build everything anymore,

00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:50.500
he mostly does code review.

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:51.739
But this is what he had to say about

00:12:51.739 --> 00:12:53.619
incorporating rust into the Linux kernel.

00:12:53.619 --> 00:12:56.340
He said that it not only made technical sense,

00:12:56.340 --> 00:12:59.859
but it was mostly, we don't wanna stagnate as a kernel.

00:12:59.859 --> 00:13:03.059
Linux kernel is almost a 30-year-old project,

00:13:03.059 --> 00:13:04.340
and they are still trying,

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:06.500
they are very hesitant of trying new things,

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:08.580
but rust is motivating them to try new things.

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:10.140
And I think that talks to the culture

00:13:10.140 --> 00:13:13.700
of what rust is bringing to the different ecosystems.

00:13:13.700 --> 00:13:15.140
All of the tools that I'm showing on screen,

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:19.099
and there are many more, are heavily inspired

00:13:19.099 --> 00:13:21.020
by things that might have come from other languages,

00:13:21.020 --> 00:13:24.159
but at rust, kind of push towards the community.

00:13:24.159 --> 00:13:28.440
So if anyone's tried air, air has a little notice

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:30.200
that says, hey, this is very inspired

00:13:30.200 --> 00:13:31.919
by a lot of different packages,

00:13:31.919 --> 00:13:33.599
one of them being cargo format,

00:13:33.599 --> 00:13:35.359
so the format from rust.

00:13:35.359 --> 00:13:38.320
Or RV, like if you tried dependency management with RV,

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:39.799
that's heavily inspired by UV,

00:13:39.799 --> 00:13:42.440
and UV's heavily inspired by something like cargo,

00:13:42.440 --> 00:13:44.840
which is the rust package manager.

00:13:44.840 --> 00:13:45.960
There are a bunch of tools

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:48.239
that rust has enabled people to do,

00:13:48.239 --> 00:13:49.799
and that's when I talk about culture,

00:13:49.799 --> 00:13:52.400
I speak over there, about how it empowers people.

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:54.799
And that goes back to the definition of rust.

00:13:54.799 --> 00:13:58.119
So rust is a language that, in a technical sense,

00:13:58.119 --> 00:13:59.859
yeah, it makes sense, whatever,

00:13:59.859 --> 00:14:01.880
but most importantly, it is a language

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:05.000
that's empowering everyone to build efficient,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.280
performant, reliable software.

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:09.020
And what does that mean for R?

00:14:09.020 --> 00:14:11.479
Well, that we can make R more reliable,

00:14:11.479 --> 00:14:13.440
we can make R more performant,

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:16.039
and we can also make R much more productive.

00:14:17.679 --> 00:14:18.960
So this is a big question

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:21.580
that I've actually been asked by many people,

00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:23.820
it's like, hey, should my organization

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:25.020
consider adopting rust?

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:27.440
Or, eh, we don't know about it.

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:28.700
So the question is,

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:31.979
should your organization consider adopting rust?

00:14:31.979 --> 00:14:34.299
My answer would be yes.

00:14:34.299 --> 00:14:36.340
And yes, not in the sense that,

00:14:36.340 --> 00:14:37.900
yeah, go all in on rust,

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:40.580
everyone, all your team needs to now write rust

00:14:40.580 --> 00:14:43.200
instead of R or Python, that's not the case.

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:46.739
Because what we try to do is extend instead of replace.

00:14:46.739 --> 00:14:51.140
We don't wanna rewrite all your data analysis tools

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:54.500
and your data engineering from R or from Python to rust,

00:14:54.500 --> 00:14:56.020
we want to extend.

00:14:56.020 --> 00:14:58.059
The project is literally called Extender,

00:14:58.059 --> 00:15:00.179
like, that's kind of the point.

00:15:00.179 --> 00:15:02.659
So you don't need to know everything about rust

00:15:02.659 --> 00:15:04.219
to start adopting rust.

00:15:04.219 --> 00:15:05.419
So the barrier to entry,

00:15:05.419 --> 00:15:07.679
the cost to start using rust in your organization,

00:15:07.679 --> 00:15:09.179
it's not really that high.

00:15:10.039 --> 00:15:12.419
If you wanna start learning about how to use Extender

00:15:12.419 --> 00:15:14.580
and wanna write your first little package

00:15:14.580 --> 00:15:16.859
that maybe calls into a function in rust,

00:15:16.859 --> 00:15:18.380
please scan that QR code.

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:20.580
With that QR code, you will be able to

00:15:20.859 --> 00:15:21.780
get into the user guide.

00:15:21.780 --> 00:15:24.340
The user guide is written by a dear friend

00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:26.900
and it's very complete.

00:15:28.260 --> 00:15:30.020
If you wanna get into more serious rust,

00:15:30.020 --> 00:15:32.460
so if you wanna start doing, perhaps, tools,

00:15:32.460 --> 00:15:33.900
maybe you want to write a tool

00:15:33.900 --> 00:15:36.260
to fix a very specific problem,

00:15:36.260 --> 00:15:37.979
then I would highly advise you read

00:15:37.979 --> 00:15:40.000
the Rust Programming Language book.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.659
It covers a lot of things about rust,

00:15:42.659 --> 00:15:45.099
not everything, but everything you need

00:15:45.099 --> 00:15:46.580
to start writing tools, for example.

00:15:46.580 --> 00:15:49.580
So if you wanna write the next formatter,

00:15:49.619 --> 00:15:50.580
it's kind of a soft problem,

00:15:50.580 --> 00:15:52.219
but if you wanna write the next AR

00:15:52.219 --> 00:15:54.820
or the next RV or the next whatever,

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:55.940
I would highly suggest you start

00:15:55.940 --> 00:15:58.599
with the Rust Programming Language book.

00:15:58.599 --> 00:16:01.739
And I would also advise you run the Rust in Data community.

00:16:01.739 --> 00:16:03.099
So this is a newsletter

00:16:03.099 --> 00:16:04.640
and we'll be having a monthly hangout

00:16:04.640 --> 00:16:07.739
where we send news and things about the intersection

00:16:07.739 --> 00:16:08.940
between rust and data.

00:16:10.059 --> 00:16:13.140
The next iteration of the newsletter

00:16:13.140 --> 00:16:15.299
will actually have a newer package

00:16:15.299 --> 00:16:18.619
that uses rust from behind to make some things

00:16:18.619 --> 00:16:21.780
really fast and really performant and really efficient.

00:16:21.780 --> 00:16:23.460
So have a rust evening.

00:16:23.460 --> 00:16:24.619
It's not really evening yet,

00:16:24.619 --> 00:16:27.979
but now I've made this talk specifically

00:16:27.979 --> 00:16:30.820
a little bit shorter to have a bunch of time for Q&A

00:16:30.820 --> 00:16:32.099
because I know this is a topic

00:16:32.099 --> 00:16:33.380
that maybe a lot of you guys,

00:16:33.380 --> 00:16:35.419
it's the first time you hear about it.

00:16:35.419 --> 00:16:38.219
So yeah, let's get into Q&A.

00:16:38.219 --> 00:16:39.679
I don't know.

00:16:39.679 --> 00:16:40.520
Thanks.

00:16:40.659 --> 00:16:41.500
Thank you.

00:16:48.799 --> 00:16:49.900
So the first question is how many of you

00:16:49.900 --> 00:16:51.400
have had the experience of spinning a package

00:16:51.400 --> 00:16:53.500
with CRAN that came from?

00:16:53.500 --> 00:16:56.500
I've spoken to, like every single time

00:16:59.599 --> 00:17:02.400
I speak to someone, I was like what, what CRAN?

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:07.400
So, it's a not that pleasant of an experience

00:17:11.079 --> 00:17:12.459
but it is doable.

00:17:12.459 --> 00:17:14.400
So, for example, when we were submitting

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:18.079
Orweaver to CRAN, we probably had like five iterations

00:17:18.079 --> 00:17:19.199
of them coming back to us.

00:17:19.199 --> 00:17:21.780
Yeah, but this, there are certain rules

00:17:21.780 --> 00:17:25.280
in the way that CRAN validates in their automatic checking

00:17:25.280 --> 00:17:28.439
that use like a really old Rust version.

00:17:28.439 --> 00:17:30.199
Why, because they want to guarantee

00:17:30.199 --> 00:17:33.339
backwards compatibility with really old systems

00:17:33.339 --> 00:17:36.699
but that makes a challenge that things move fast, right?

00:17:36.699 --> 00:17:38.380
So we don't wanna work with like a three year old

00:17:38.380 --> 00:17:40.140
version of Rust, we wanna work with like,

00:17:40.140 --> 00:17:42.099
maybe like a two year old version of Rust

00:17:42.099 --> 00:17:43.979
would be better than a three year old version of Rust.

00:17:43.979 --> 00:17:47.099
So yeah, the submitting packages to CRAN

00:17:47.099 --> 00:17:49.260
can be a little bit of a headache but it's doable.

00:17:49.260 --> 00:17:52.500
If you're a decent person and you talk to them

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:55.219
like a decent person, you'll get through

00:17:55.219 --> 00:17:57.380
but that's definitely something to improve.

00:18:02.780 --> 00:18:05.780
How does Xamarin.org compare to RCD?

00:18:09.239 --> 00:18:10.800
So R Extender is really cool.

00:18:13.540 --> 00:18:16.640
There are many ways of extending R packages

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:21.640
but R Extender uses Rust's guarantees

00:18:22.339 --> 00:18:23.979
which I don't wanna get into the details

00:18:23.979 --> 00:18:28.979
but it really maps the R data types into Rust really well

00:18:29.699 --> 00:18:30.540
and it works really well.

00:18:30.540 --> 00:18:32.180
So I'm gonna go back actually to the slide

00:18:32.180 --> 00:18:34.079
where I showed like the little snippet.

00:18:34.079 --> 00:18:39.079
So this is a snippet of X Extender, right?

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:45.439
And you have this type strings,

00:18:45.439 --> 00:18:50.199
strings is like the characters array in R

00:18:50.199 --> 00:18:55.199
and you just can use it like you would use any type in Rust.

00:18:55.359 --> 00:18:57.800
You don't need to do anything else to implement it.

00:18:57.800 --> 00:18:59.319
Of course, there are edge cases,

00:18:59.319 --> 00:19:01.680
there are cases where things don't translate as well

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:04.239
but the fact that I can just write this function,

00:19:04.239 --> 00:19:08.119
now I have an 18 times faster version than my,

00:19:08.119 --> 00:19:11.920
it's magical and it's really easy for certain things.

00:19:11.920 --> 00:19:14.319
It's harder for other things but also the problems

00:19:14.319 --> 00:19:16.239
that you need to solve to do harder things are harder.

00:19:16.239 --> 00:19:19.199
So I think it's a really pleasant experience

00:19:19.199 --> 00:19:21.359
especially compared to RCPP, for example.

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:24.599
Okay, last question.

00:19:24.599 --> 00:19:26.719
Your experience, have you used L1

00:19:26.719 --> 00:19:29.920
and you're helping to translate more into Rust?

00:19:29.920 --> 00:19:31.319
Yes.

00:19:31.319 --> 00:19:34.400
So mostly, kind of, yeah.

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:39.400
So we had this geospatial problem

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:44.680
that we did to kind of get,

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:47.599
like calculate what's the nearest beach

00:19:47.599 --> 00:19:49.819
and we had all that code in R

00:19:49.819 --> 00:19:51.560
and it basically one-shotted it

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:54.599
except for using like some deprecated functions

00:19:54.599 --> 00:19:57.400
because the training data used like old GDAL functions

00:19:57.400 --> 00:19:59.439
instead of new GDAL functions

00:19:59.439 --> 00:20:00.520
but that was an easy fix

00:20:00.520 --> 00:20:04.000
but other than that, it basically one-shotted it.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.400
And other times, it just gets it absolutely wrong

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:08.520
but that's kind of what we've seen like in talks

00:20:08.520 --> 00:20:10.719
like L1s are sometimes, like it's unpredictable

00:20:10.719 --> 00:20:12.380
whether they're gonna do good or bad.

00:20:12.380 --> 00:20:15.839
You do need to know Rust to evaluate the harder problems

00:20:15.839 --> 00:20:17.959
but for the easier problems,

00:20:17.959 --> 00:20:20.640
again, for a function as small as this,

00:20:20.640 --> 00:20:22.199
it will one-shot this function.

00:20:23.839 --> 00:20:25.040
All right, that's it from me.

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:25.880
Thank you so much.

00:20:25.880 --> 00:20:26.719
Thank you.

